main event: A bright, blinking light was observed visually and on radar near Ketchikan, Alaska on June 13, 1960.
interesting points: The object was tracked on radar and observed visually for about 1 minute.
The object approached and brightened, then disappeared from both visual and radar observation.
The object was initially thought to possibly be a meteor, aircraft, or satellite reentry, but the conclusion was that there was insufficient information to evaluate its identity.
A fishing vessel in the area also reported seeing a gradually brightening and dimming object in the sky for about 30 minutes.
The location and sighting details suggest the object was likely the planet Venus.
witnesses: Ground-based radar operators and a fishing vessel crew
photographs: No photographs present in the report
